## Mobile usability and performance recommendations

The visible experience is visually polished, but the site would benefit from cleaner text legibility, stronger static explanatory copy, and careful image optimization. The hero and product layouts are image-heavy and stylized, which is good for brand feel but can create friction if text contrast, viewport density, or asset weight is not tightly managed. Because the site runs on Vercel and Next.js, Aviera should lean on optimized image delivery, pre-sized Open Graph assets, and aggressive use of statically rendered content where possible.

| Area | Recommendation |
|---|---|
| Typography | Increase legibility of subhead copy and small text on mobile |
| Image weight | Use optimized formats and compress product media |
| Structured text | Add crawlable copy above or near interactive modules |
| CLS risk | Reserve space for media and sticky UI elements |
| Cookie banner | Avoid obscuring core conversion CTAs on small screens |

## Final strategic recommendation

Aviera does not need a radically different brand strategy. It needs a more complete search and answer-engine expression of the strategy it already has. The most effective positioning is **performance supplements with guided personalization**, not personalization in isolation. If Aviera fixes the crawl layer, rewrites page metadata and headings in real search language, adds structured data and trust architecture, and publishes tightly aligned educational content, it can become much easier for both Google and AI assistants to understand and recommend.

That is the central opportunity: build the site so that a human shopper, a search engine, and an AI assistant all arrive at the same conclusion about what Aviera is and who it helps.

